          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Vultures at the Gates</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">When Argentina defaulted on $132 billion in debt in 2001, it faced one of its worst economic crises, with poverty and unemployment skyrocketing, sparking a decade-long battle with holdout investors. In two rounds of debt restructuring, Argentina convinced most creditors (93%) to accept bonds worth only a fraction of their original value, helping the country rebuild its economy. However, a small group of investors—later called "vulture funds"—bought Argentine bonds at rock-bottom prices after the default, demanding full repayment at face value and refusing the restructuring terms. The most prominent among these was NML Capital, a subsidiary of Elliott Management.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-nov-6-1.jpg" alt="Vultures at the Gates" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In 2012, a U.S. court ruled in favor of these holdouts, mandating Argentina pay them in full before it could resume payments to other creditors, creating a complex legal and financial struggle for Argentina. In 2016, Argentina finally agreed to a settlement under severe pressure, leading to an extraordinary profit of nearly $2 billion for Elliott's NML and other holdout investors.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">This case, involving legal battles and even the seizure of an Argentine naval vessel in Ghana, highlighted the enormous power of hedge funds in global debt markets and sparked debates on the ethics and consequences of such tactics for struggling nations. Critics argue this win encouraged further "vulture" behavior, potentially hindering other countries' efforts to restructure debt in times of crisis, with implications for global financial stability.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">This case reshaped the landscape of international debt restructuring, as legal victories like this one create a precedent for profit-seeking holdouts and encourage similar behavior worldwide, even prompting some countries to outlaw specific "vulture" tactics. However, with broader international reform, cases like Argentina's highlight the need for more protections for sovereign nations in debt crises, leaving them vulnerable to influential financial players.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
